               <p>554. <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <persName id="def1-554-18560514" type="defendantName">
                        <interp inst="def1-554-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def1-554-18560514" type="age" value="38"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def1-554-18560514" type="surname" value="BEALE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def1-554-18560514" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BEALE</persName>,<persName id="def2-554-18560514" type="defendantName">
                        <interp inst="def2-554-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def2-554-18560514" type="age" value="39"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def2-554-18560514" type="surname" value="MURPHY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def2-554-18560514" type="given" value="PATRICK"></interp> PATRICK MURPHY</persName>
                  </hi>, and <persName id="def3-554-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def3-554-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-554-18560514" type="surname" value="MURPHY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-554-18560514" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">DANIEL MURPHY</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18560514-554-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18560514-554-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18560514-554-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, stealing a quantity of leather, value 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18560514-name-593" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-593" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-593" type="surname" value="CROSSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-593" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-593" type="occupation" value="currier"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-554-offence-1 t18560514-name-593"></join>James Crossley</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140323"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-594" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-594" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-594" type="surname" value="BURBIDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-594" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BURBIDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a boot maker, and live in Douglas-street Deptford. I have known Besle these twenty years—I saw him on 26th March, he said he had lost sight of me for some time, and he could have put a few pounds in my way—I said, "In what way?"—he said, about some leather that was got <hi rend="italic">on the cross</hi>, and he supposed I did not mind buying it <hi rend="italic">on the cross</hi>—I said, "No," and I asked him how much there was of it—he said, there was a pretty good <hi rend="italic">swag</hi>, but the greater part was gone—I asked him how much he could get of it—he said he did not know exactly, but he would see me again—I appointed to see him in about an hour or an hour end a half—when he was gone I went to Mr. Crossley's, I had heard he had lost some leather—I saw Beale again at the top of Douglas-street, I asked him where the man lived who had the leather, and whether I should go with him—he said, no, perhaps, he should not see him till night—I saw Beale again on the following day, but he said he could not get it—on the Saturday morning he came to my house with a piece of leather bound round him, under his clothes (my daughter opened the door)—he took it out, and I saw it was Mr. Crossley's, it had his dressers' mark and the number—I asked him how much he asked for it—he said 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I said, "I must get you to call again in half an hour, and then I will make it all right"—he went away and I went out the other way—I rather think he watched me—he came back to my house, but I was not at home.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-595" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-595" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-595" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-595" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Davis, and daughter of the last witness—I was at his house on 29th March, I remember Beale coming—he asked for my father, and they went in the parlour and stood talking—I went in the kitchen—my father went out and I asked Beale whether he would stay or call again in half an hour—he said he would call again—he went away, and in three or four minutes Beale came back and said he wanted the leather for my father, who was waiting at the end of the street—I said, I would not give it up except my father came—Beale staid some time and went away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-596" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-596" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-596" type="surname" value="CROSSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-596" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CROSSLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a currier and live in Church-street, Deptford. On 26th March I received some communication from Burbidge—on 19th March my place was broken into, and some leather taken away—on 29th March I received this piece of leather from Mr. Burbidge—it is the same description of leather that I had, but my foreman will speak to it more fully.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-597" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-597" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-597" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-597" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Mr. Crossley—this leather is his property—it is part of what was stolen—I saw it safe on the evening of 19th March, and missed it on the morning of the 20th—this piece formed the outside of a bundle of twenty-eight pieces—here are my own initials on it—it is part of a hide cut in two, and my own mark is on it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-598" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-598" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-598" type="surname" value="TURNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-598" type="given" value="JOSIAH"></interp>JOSIAH TURNER</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">policeman, R</hi> 307). I was on duty at Deptford on 20th March, and I received information of the robbery—on 28th March I met Beale on Deptford-bridge—he said to me, "Are you looking after a certain party, Jem, the currier?"—I said, "No"—he said, "You are aware there has been a robbery at Mr. Crossley's?"—I said, "Yes"—he said, "I thought you were looking after it"—I said, "No, I was not"—he then said he thought he could find out something about it, if I met him the following morning at 9 o'clock he should be able to give me some information—he said, he should be able to go in the tap room amongst the men, and should hear something more about it—he said, they were two Irishmen, living in Giffin-street—I went at 9 o'clock and waited till 20 minutes to ten o'clock—he did not come—I did not see him till the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140324"></xptr>
               <p>evening—on the Saturday evening I took Beale into custody at the corner by the Prince Regent public house—the other two prisoners were with him—I told Beale I should charge him with being concerned in stealing the leather—I said to him, "Do those other two know anything about it?"—he said, "They do"—and an officer took them into custody—in going along, Beale said he was very sorry he had not brought the leather to me instead of taking it to Burbidge, and he should have been all right—at the station he said he had received the leather from <hi rend="italic">Pat</hi> Murphy, and Patrick Murphy struck him a violent blow on the eye, using an oath.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Beale.</hi> You said, "If you can make out anything about the leather with the two Murphys, do. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I do not believe I mentioned the name of Murphy.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-599" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-599" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-599" type="surname" value="WILSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-599" type="given" value="WILLIAM BEEVES"></interp>WILLIAM BEEVES WILSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a police inspector—I assisted in taking Patrick and Daniel Murphy to the station—I took the charge and explained that they were charged with stealing a quantity of leather from Mr. Crossley, in Church-street, Deptford—Beale said he had received the leather, which was then lying there, from <hi rend="italic">Pat</hi> Murphy, and Patrick Murphy struck him and became violent, and he was removed—Daniel Murphy said, as Beale had implicated his brother, he would tell me all about it—I took him out in the yard, and he said, "A man named Jem, the currier, asked me to lend him a hand to drive a barrow with the leather up to London; I did so, and he took it to a shop in Bermondsey-street and sold it, and he gave me 25<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. as my part"—he said, "We left the barrow in the street; that is all I know about it"—I asked him if he knew where the shop was—he said he thought he should be able to find it if he was taken there—he was not taken there, but we inquired at all the shops in Bermondsey-street, and they knew nothing of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Daniel Murphy. Q.</hi> When you took me, was I drunk or sober? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> You were sober, you had been drinking a little, but you knew what you were saying, and I cautioned you before you spoke—I did not come to you on the Sunday morning at the cell door, and ask you if you knew what you had said.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-600" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-600" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-600" type="surname" value="CROSSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-600" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CROSSLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> On the night that Daniel Murphy was taken, I merely walked to the station and gave the charge—Daniel Murphy was sober.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-601" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-601" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-601" type="surname" value="CROUCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-601" type="given" value="ALFRED JOHN"></interp>ALFRED JOHN CROUCH</persName>
                  </hi>, (<hi rend="italic">policeman, R</hi> 92). I assisted in taking the Murphys to the station—Daniel Murphy was sober, and perfectly able to judge of his own actions—when we arrived at the station Beale put his hand on Patrick Murphy, and said, "This is the man that I had the leather from"—Patrick Murphy struck him a blow on the eye, and he was removed—I left, and went to search Murphy's house in Giffin-street—I found no<lb></lb>thing there—Daniel Murphy said he wished to tell the inspector something—I accompanied the inspector into the yard, and he said he had assisted to take the leather to Bermondsey-street, and he had 25<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for his share—I came in again, and saw this leather on the table—I said to Patrick Murphy, "How do you account for this?"—he said "I picked it up in a passage of a house"—he would not say where the house was.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Beale's Defence.</hi> I received this leather from Patrick Murphy; he first told me of it, and it was a week afterwards before I got it; I took it to Mr. Burbidge, and asked him 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it; he offered me 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; I am perfectly innocent of the robbery.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Patrick Murphy's Defence.</hi> I was going to work at 6 o'clock in the morning, and saw a door partly open; no person had lived in the house for</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140325"></xptr>
               <p>six months; I saw this piece of leather, and picked it up; I told Beale I had found it, and I did not know what sort it was; I saw him five or six days afterwards, and he asked me if I had sold it; I said "No," and I gave him the leather; I know nothing of it; any person might go in that house, and sleep for a night; there has been no rent paid for the house for above twelve months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-602" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-602" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-602" type="surname" value="CROSSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-602" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CROSSLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This piece of leather produced is worth about 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the whole I lost was worth about 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
